\section{Random-intercept topology (the \code{grouping} attribute)}{

For random-intercept models (no random slope) the one-way / nested / crossed
topology is reported separately in \code{attr(result, "grouping")}
(\code{"oneway"}, \code{"nested"}, or \code{"crossed"}); it is \code{NA} for random-slope models.
}

\section{Extrapolation in time (slope models)}{

For the random-slope and fixed-slope models the between-group variance
\verb{V_G(t0) = z0' Sigma z0} is quadratic in the time covariate. Evaluating an
interval at a time point outside the observed range therefore extrapolates
that quadratic; the package computes it without a guard or warning, so
out-of-range \code{t0} should be requested knowingly.
}

\section{new_group_mean (CInew / new-batch-mean)}{

\code{\link[=new_group_mean_lmm]{new_group_mean_lmm()}} is the CInew / new-batch-mean interval --- a
prediction interval for the mean of one new, as-yet-unobserved group/batch
(the prediction interval with the residual component removed). It is listed
here under both names so it is discoverable as "CInew" or "new batch mean".
}

\section{One-sided intervals}{

One-sided intervals (sides = "lower" or "upper") are currently available only
for the Montes single-observation tolerance interval and the random-slope
engines. The expected-mean-square (EMS) engine used for random-intercept and
balanced fixed-slope designs produces two-sided intervals only; one-sided EMS
intervals are planned for a future release.
}

